CyCTF25 – I Hate Tasks 

Challenge Overview

Category: Web

Backend: Node.js (Express.js) + SQLite

The target is a web application that allows users to create and manage tasks. Users can add tasks and mark them as completed or incomplete.

Because this is a white-box challenge, we are given access to the source code and can analyze the application logic directly.

Initial Observations

On application startup:

The backend creates an administrator account with a random username and password.

The flag is stored inside a task belonging to the admin user.

This immediately tells us:

Our goal is to impersonate or gain access to the admin user’s session.

Once authenticated as admin, retrieving tasks will reveal the flag.

Application Structure

The backend consists of:

An authentication router (auth)

A tasks router (tasks)

An additional /visit route that simulates an admin login

The application uses Express Session for session management.

Authentication Logic Review
Register Route

Properly validates input types

Creates a user securely

Sets session variables:

loggedUser: username

authenticated: boolean flag

Login Route

Works similarly to register

Sets the same session variables

Logout Route

Destroys the session correctly

At this point, authentication logic looks solid and not directly exploitable.

Tasks Router Analysis

The tasks router contains several critical implementation flaws.

Key Components

A blacklist array called excludedFields, containing dangerous keys such as __proto__

A _Task class responsible for:

Fetching tasks

Updating tasks

Saving tasks

Critical Issue: Unsafe Object Binding

The application dynamically assigns user-controlled fields into objects using key-value iteration. This creates a Server-Side Prototype Pollution vulnerability.

Although a blacklist exists, its implementation is flawed.

Identified Vulnerabilities
1. Mass Assignment

User input is blindly assigned to task objects.

2. Arbitrary task_id Usage

The PATCH route:

Takes task_id from the URL

Also accepts task_id from the request body

Passes both into the _Task constructor

This allows interaction with tasks belonging to other users.

3. Prototype Pollution (Critical)

Although __proto__ is blacklisted:

The blacklist check happens after the first assignment

This allows pollution if __proto__ is sent as the first body parameter

Prototype Pollution Exploitation
Exploitation Strategy

Create a valid task as a normal user

Send a PATCH request to update the task

In the request body:

Set task_id to __proto__

Place the malicious field as the first parameter

The blacklist is bypassed due to incorrect validation order

This successfully pollutes the JavaScript object prototype.

Verifying Prototype Pollution

To confirm pollution:

A dummy object is created after the attack

The injected property appears on the new object

This confirms successful global prototype pollution.

Session Manipulation

Direct modification of these fields is blocked:

loggedUser

authenticated

username

However, there is an important observation:

Both req and req.session are JavaScript objects

Due to prototype pollution, we can manipulate the entire session object

By injecting properties into the session prototype, we can manually add:

loggedUser

authenticated

Authentication Bypass

After polluting the session object:

We send a GET request to /tasks without any session cookies

The application treats us as authenticated

This confirms a full authentication bypass.

Admin Account Takeover via /visit

The admin username is random and unknown.

However, the /visit route:

Simulates an admin login internally

Uses the same session object

Because the session object was polluted and converted into a shared global object:

When the admin logs in

Their session variables are written to the polluted object

All users inherit the admin session

Final Exploitation Flow

Pollute the session object via task update

Trigger the /visit route

Send a GET request to /tasks

The application treats the attacker as the admin

Admin tasks are returned

The flag is revealed

Flag Retrieval

Once authenticated as admin, fetching tasks exposes the admin’s task containing the flag.

Root Cause Explanation

JavaScript prototype pollution turned a private session object into a shared global object

Node.js is single-threaded, so polluted prototypes affect all users

The admin login populated shared session fields

All users inherited admin privileges
